Ask it to divide 2 lbs 13 oz by 6. It gives back 1/3 lb 13 oz. Mathematically incorrect. Any ingredient that has two units (lbs, oz) it will only divide the first one and simply leave the 2nd untouched. It will still display it like it divided it, though, leading you to mess up your recipie before you realize what went wrong.
Reply content: Hello Ben.  It will convert the 13 oz if you place a "##" in front of it (##13 oz).  Because recipes are formatted in a variety of ways, the converter only converts the first number in the line.  It will also convert numbers marked with a "##" in front of it.  Please email us or click on the support button.  We can help with more examples.

Please reach out to us at support@mykitchencalculator.com and we can help to troubleshoot why the app is not downloading on your device.

If you would like to learn to use the app, you can press the support button or contact us at support@mykitchencalculator.com.  We will be more than happy to help!

Content: Try to split a large batch recipe that I use at work and it won't break the recipe down

Hi Matthew, 

Sorry to hear that the app did not break the recipe down.  The recipe converter is very sensitive to text formatting and this may be the cause of the issue.  Please visit the support section for details.  If that does not help, please contact us at: support@mykitchencalculator.com and we can provide further support.

Reply content: Hello Simon. Sorry to hear the app did not meet your expectations. Although it is just a calculator, the area where this app shines is the ability to convert by ingredient quantity and ability to convert quickly from ingredient weights to cups and spoons.  Please feel free to contact us and we can send  you an example on how to use these features.

Thank you for helping us identify that the copy and paste issue is from using the built in Samsung internet app on your device and that using Google Chrome allowed you to paste as normal. We opened a support ticket with Google to try to address this issue. If you have other needs please contact us at support@mykitchencalculator.com.

Content: I bought and downloaded this app because I thought it included the function to paste a recipe in, say, US measuments, and get the metric equivalent as an output. But it doesn't do that. Reply content:
Hello Jorgen,

We apologize if the recipe converter tool wasn't able to automatically convert your pasted recipe from US to metric units. The app comes with unit conversion tools that can convert between US and metric. You can manually convert units and paste back into the recipe converter. We are currently studying how to make this process easier.

Hello Ben,

Thanks for providing the feedback! We have redesigned our app and have added the ingredients you requested as well as many others. If there are any additional ingredients you would like us to add, please do not hesitate to contact us at support@mykitchencalculator.com.

This app is not compatible with Chromebooks, although it says it is. The game left me with a black screen while it continued in the background. I would also not advise you to use it on a tablet as the distance between 'buttons' is much further than if playing on a tiny mobile phone. Although I can understand that it is trying to analyse strategy, it's not an effective method of understanding a candidates thought processes. Hopefully this is not the way recruitment processes are moving...more and more impersonal.
Reply content: Hi Devin. Thank you for your feedback. We are sorry to hear that you experienced technical issues and have passed your feedback onto the relevant team. Our assessments measure aspects of personality and cognition that have been deemed as important for the role you applied for.

Content: I do not believe anyone has the ability to press buttons at the speed of light. Near impossible! Most of the questions are about speed, yet at the end you will receive a 6 page report with a variety of characteristics. In the engineering question, if too slow or too fast large signs will go up and cover the boxes, making it hard to get back into playing. Why not ask situational questions? Why use animation instead of real Human faces in the emotion question? I'm Lucky this job wasn't a big deal
Reply content: Hi Natasha, please be assured psychometric science forms the foundation of our assessments, which measures aspects of cognition & personality important for the role. It is not designed to mirror the role itself. To remove bias among candidates, we use computerised images to control of the emotions and the intensity among different genders & races.

Content: App was alright albeit the exercises were completely silly and followed no logical pattern at times. The results were the worst part since they made absolutely no sense. I have never had something of this sort (a test or quiz) describe me more inaccurately. So proceed with caution... why this would be used in professional settings is beyond me.

Most of the topics were based off reaction time. Not something I would consider a requirement for a job. Some of the parts of the assessment felt like they were trying to get you to analyse a pattern of slme sort but it was just random. And poorly rendered facial expressions made it difficult to determine the correct answers for some parts. The verbal test was the only highlight. A company that uses this app to determine whether or not you get the job. Maybe I'd be fine not working for them.
Reply content: Hi Deighton. Thanks for your feedback. Our assessments measure 33 personality and cognitive traits that are deemed important for the role you applied for. Our levels are based on validated, neuroscientific research.

Content: I do not feel that a task like this is an accurate reflection of how I would perform in a professional environment or reflect anybodies skillset at all. It was simply memory and hand eye coordination, this does not reflect how people may interact with potential clients or how they would manage their work load in the slightest. This is akin to the personality tests that are popular currently. Whilst something a bit different the fact is that different is not always better or good.
Reply content: Hi Sean, the tasks in our assessmentl are not designed to mirror tasks in the role you had applied for - instead, they are measuring aspects of personality using a series of validated and academically accepted tasks.

Content: I had to complete this test to apply for an engineering position. Every game is entirely about reaction time. I spent over an hour attempting the lock picking question as it was literally impossible. The object moved so fast that my screen couldn't refresh and update adequately. I think by using the app it has made me see that maybe i shouldn't work for the company.
Reply content: Hi Max. Thanks for your feedback. Our assessments measure over 33 cognitive and personality traits that are deemed important for the role you applied for, and each level is based on a validated neuroscience experiment.

Content: This is impossible for users with a learning difficulty such as Dyscalculia/Dyspraxia. Particularly the unlocking task and the directions task. We need more time to process large amounts of information and that's impossible when it moves on in one second if you're deemed 'too slow'. I really feel singled out because of my difficulty. The even/odd task, tablet price and directions were too difficult and not user friendly for all. Feels very unfair to be judged.
Reply content: Hi there, we provide reasonable adjustments for learning difficulties. Please email the organisation you had applied to and they will be able to apply the reasonable adjustments for you even after you had completed the assessment.

Content: The absolute worst application process I have ever participated in. Mostly assesses your reaction time. The electrical lever level made no sense at all. The balloon level is a total joke. The facial recognition is hilarious at best (also no need to move the tiles for selecting the facial expression). Companies who use this in their application process should be embarrassed.
Reply content: Hi Cameron. Please be assured psychometric science forms the foundation of our assessments. The tasks are measuring aspects of cognition & personality that are important for the role. These tests are based on established cognitive tasks that have been used for decades, and the gamification features are known to increase candidate experience.

Content: Hello I have downloaded the app to do my assessment however it won't allow me to out in my password I have uninstall it 3 times and reinstalled it and it is just the same. I can only put it my username. I have also attempted on my laptop and still the same. My WiFi is perfectly fine. Ive been trying to get in touch with someone to help and nothing!
Reply content: Hi, were you getting in touch with support@arcticshores.com? This is our email and during our working hours we typically get back within 2 hours. Content: awful. the instructions aren't clear enough to formulate a strategy for some tasks and others are just pure luck. on top of that a few of the games are reaction speed based which is just discriminatory towards people who have a disability that effects their reaction speed. oh and the game with the faces is garbage, I've never seen a human that uses expressions like some of those images.
Reply content: Hi there, please be assured psychometric science forms the foundation of our assessments. The tasks are measuring aspects of cognition & personality that are important for the role. We used computerised images to standardise the emotions.

Content: The level of arrogance displayed in the reactions given by the developer here, pretending they have developed the perfect personality test. About the game, the one with the two teams: are we going for profit maximization? The fact that there are two opposing teams would make you think so. Think again, it's about altruism. Really? The ones with the balloons and the electricity felt way too random to be really meaningful. And the faces were too poorly drawn for giving insight in emotion recognition
Reply content: Thank you for your review. Each level is based on a scientifically valid, neuroscientific study and measures traits that are deemed important for the role you applied for. We measure up to 33 traits across the whole study, some of which are assessed in a subtle fashion.

Content: Fun but terrifying! The games itself doesn't feel like a tedious assement however my results are nothing like how I approach my work, it makes me sounds impulsive and emotional which isn't me at all, it's terrifying to think that from a few games this inaccurate representation of me is going to be used to see if I'm right for a job. Thanks but no thanks, feel like I've lost all chances of getting this job.
Reply content: Hi Chloe, I am sorry that you feel this way about the assessment - It may help to take a look at this article that covers some of the reasons why you may not see yourself in your results: https://knowledgebase.arcticshores.com/knowledge/i-disagree-with-my-results

Content: Despite the repeated claims that psychometric science forms the basis, I can honestly say its a load of rubbish!! Apparently your results are thought to be stable to your personality for several months, but having done this test over 20 times, I get a completely different result each time in the feedback pdf!! I honestly think it's really shocking and a real shame that employers are now using these methods to filter out recruits. What a sad sign of the times.
Reply content: Hi Sam, I am sorry that you feel this way. We do not suggest that the test should be repeated many times in quick succession. We aim to measure intuitive choices and behaviours, which is best caught on the first attempt of completing the assessment. If you want to talk about this further, please feel free to reach out to support@arcticshores.com

Content: A thoroughly disappointing experience. I was left deeply unimpressed by what seemed to be a series of tests of reaction rather than anything else. This was the first time I have had an Arctic Shores psychometric test for a job, and if I see another position that requires one, it will be a negative consideration in a decision to apply.
Reply content: Hi Curtis, please be assured psychometric science forms the foundation of our assessments. The tasks are measuring aspects of cognition & personality that are important for the role.

Content: Overall this wasnt too bad however I dont believe this game should determine whether or not I get a job, I spent hours trying the final task and completed it only to find it had no real impact on my score, this is fun and enjoyable with a little bit of challeng to it however it has nothing to do with the job I'm applying for, this app has potential but it's not yet at the level to determine someone's future, the game or "assessment" is mostly a reaction test mostly based off luck.
Reply content: Hi, I am sorry about the concerns you have. The assessment is designed to get the most out of you from an engagement point of view while measuring your behavioral traits in the background. It is these traits that are used to establish progression, rather than your reactions or score. Do contact us at support@arcticshores.com if your still concerned

Content: A lot of the levels seem to be based on luck making the game incredibly frustrating since it's assessing you. Similarly a lot of games are based one reaction time so if your phone screen has a delay like mine then you are screwed.

Pointless and inaccurate beyond belief! You decided I was slow at data analysis yet I analyse data daily at work. Your system is flawed and any company using your software should be ashamed of themselves for latching on to psycho babble via clicking games in order to choose applicants.

I am more interested in, is understanding how inflating a balloon means something about my personality, my work ethic, my motivators. One thing for sure, wont look at a balloon the same way again. Read feedback again, actually disagree with a lot. Things that are normally key strengths in real life, apparently have now changed to weaknessess 😂 per Artic shores Feedback. Monkeys form the foundation of us. Doesnt mean there is much monkey in us today...
Reply content: Hi Gary, please be assured psychometric science forms the foundation of our assessments. Thank you for your feedback - we will work to change the wording so that it is clearer.

Content: Waste of time. These tests will not reflect and employees ability in the work space. The only worthwhile test was the last one

Not all innovations are good, sometimes companies are just trying to sell their junk under the name of science. Yes some psychological experiments upon which this game has been built are valid. However no such research has been carried out to assess the combined effect of putting together isolated experiments. Certainly nothing has been done to prove it's effectiveness in hiring. Regardless of the science this is a great drain of time compared to other non-game based tests.
Reply content: Research / validation processes are carried out using data obtained from our assessment for the purpose of predicting other psychological attributes and job performance. Our assessments are built following guidelines of best practice in test development set by the EFPA, with continuing success achieved in proving its effectiveness in hiring.

Content: Some instructions really unclear (e.g. Electric machines) Some tasks complete RNG with no skill involved. I would NEVER recommend using this app to test future employees.

Regarding the levels, while some levels do involve chance, the point is not to test how high you can score, take a look here https://landing.arcticshores.com/the-science-behind-the-assessment

Content: I am convinced the positive reviews here are bought and paid for, in majority. and others who had a bad time probably feel threatened to post their name to people in charge of their potential future job. Some assessments had practice runs and others did not, in the sense of a fair 'game-based' testing either all have a practice run or they do not. this was the first game-based i've come accross that had some with and some without. This app claims as well that people dont need a gaming background is ludicrous since some of the game are time based and would require people to be quicker than most, even if it is just tapping one button or another. would also benefit the user if an average score of an assessment for their own benefit of saying i need to be better or im going okay. A score at the end of each assessment is a nice touch but means nothing if you dont know if its a good bad or okay score. also in the final assessment it prompts the user saying you can leave this assessment at anytime however you wont be able to return to it. it should say you can leave this assessment at anytime however you will not recieve points for completion, in sense of fairness the wording should be that. Also the leaps it takes in its assessment, i would love to see the science behind it because apparently i am both, "someone who tends to deliberate carefully on decisions that take risk" and also "someone who makes decision on intuition rather than someone who makes rational based decisions". Would love to meet someone who also thinks deliberately about things yet also someone who makes decisions on their intuition, if you exist. also claims that i make decisions based on my more personal needs rather than that of others, again would love to see how my physcometric analysis of 9 game based physcometric tests concluded that. That being said their marketing team deserves props for getting a lot of companies to adopt this.
Reply content: Hi Lewis, we do not pay for positive reviews. Due to the traits we measure, we can't have practice runs for all tasks. Extensive testing has shown that there is no difference in someone’s profile whether they are a gamer or not. With regards to your feedback regarding the wording, we are currently looking into it.

Reply content: I'm sorry to hear that you didn't enjoy the Balloon Burst level. Employers are interested in the aspects of cognition and personality measured by how you approach all of the tasks in the assessment rather than your absolute performance in each task. Rest assured, no decisions are being made based on just popping balloons!

Irrelevant

Content: While all the psychology seems to be in place, and it seems there has been effort put into it, ultimately it's a failed attempt of gamification. From poorly modelled and rigged faces used to measure emotion to frame issues on a modern device. I personally don't agree with scoring a personality test, despite doing well in it, there's no need to pit people trying to find jobs against eachother. I did like the format of which they give you the results via pdf, and I do think that this app has potential

At first found this a pretty good idea. Then while actually doing the tasks I realised that you need inhuman reflexes to complete the tasks. There "fail" sound puts you off and is a destruction and has absolutely nothing in relation to your behaviour or probl solving skills as some tasks are based on luck like the balloons or power charge which at 1st seems to have pattern but then randomise half way through.
Reply content: Hi, thank you for your feedback. We can assure you the assessment does not rely on luck - the tasks capture traits that make up your natural behaviour. This way, employers get an authentic picture of you and use this insight to see if you’ll be a great fit for the role. If you'd like to discuss further please email us at support@arcticshores.com

Content: I did 3 timed tests testing different skills (literacy, number sequences and shape pattern sequences) and although I feel I did very well on one test and very badly on another, I got the exact same score for each test (which strikes me as bonkers). I have no idea whether it's good or bad. I expected to get some sort of report or analysis at the end but received nothing - it told me my final score then ended the game. Will I ever find out what it all meant? I'm very confused and unsatisfied! :(
Reply content: Hi Barry, the in-game points have have no bearing on your results and are there purely for enjoyment. You will need to email the organisation you had applied to for your report, or wait until the end of the recruitment for them to send the report to you.

Content: Having not played any sort of computer game since space invaders at my local.pub in the 80's, i feel disadvantaged by not having a knowledge if gaming concepts or practiced.hand/eye coordination. Just having to figure out playstore(?) In order to access the assessment in the first place, felt like a test. Having to access and complete this assessment remotely undoubtedly generates advantages for some over others. I THOUGHT i was doing a practice run when i wasnt, and quit one game half way through . Perhaps this should be combined with a hand written psychometric test to make it more of an even playing field for those of us who prefer to hold a pen. You may not need to be brain of Brirain to figure most of these things out, but those who design on line assessments really need to account for the fact that anything is easy when you have knoweldge, experience and a better comprehension of gaming. I have NEVER done anything like this on a.phone. I have felt.torally out of.my confort zone. Its like beinga competent cook, but being challenged to make a cake only using one arm. You have then knowledge to make it, but have to figure out new ways of doing things as you go along. A one armed person is already ahead of you on that one!
Reply content: Thank you very much for your review, The Skyrise City assessment that you had completed measures different aspects of your personality, cognitive ability and decision making based on over 5,000 data points that we collect while you were immersed in the assessment. Unfortunately paper assessments isn't something we offer.

Content: I thought one of the tests was on infinite loop (safe combination), so I abandoned it after what felt like 20 minutes. Also, if you're going to test peoples' ability to read facial expressions, it might be a good idea to use real people in real situations rather than "Identi-Kit" mock-ups. If it's not real, then surely the idea is flawed. But then I'm probably a Replicant anyway ;-)
Reply content: Hi Richard and thank you for your feedback. Please be assured psychometric science forms the foundation of our assessments. We ensure every task within our game-based assessments is based on valid and reliable cognitive measures. Computerised images are used so that we can better control the facial expressions.

Content: While the concept is good, the tasks are inane and often patternless, leading to massive frustration, or impossible. The sound and visual design is irritating and distracting.
Reply content: Hi Nick, sorry that you felt that the sound and visuals were distracting. We are currently improving the overall aesthetics of the assessment at the moment. Each of the levels is explicitly based on tasks from neuroscience that have been very carefully recreated to ensure there validity, what they measure may not be directly obvious.

Content: Disappointing and not great for high functioning dyslexics Needs more audio cues. Several activities took me longer to understand, not based on my ability but by how I learn due to being dyslexic.

I did the test twice today for 2 different employers and got different results. The tests were identical. I suspect people might not be successful because of this. I bet if i did it again I'd get different results a 3rd time. I have reynauds and my fingers went numb from holding my phone so long.

Reply content: Hi there! We're sorry to hear you're having some trouble logging in. Please contact support@arcticshores.com so we can help resolve this for you.

Content: I completed the same test twice, 1 year apart and it gave me an entirely different report. Arctic Shores might try to get out of that by claiming their assessments are only valid for 9 months, but I doubt my personality did a complete U-turn in that time. The science behind these things is flaky at best, it just gives employers an excuse to not read applications if they get too many. Edit in response to reply: if that's the case, your norm group isn't big enough for repeatable comparison.
Reply content: Hi James,  please be assured psychometric science forms the foundation of our assessments. The tasks are measuring aspects of cognition & personality that are important for the role. You might be compared to a different norm group, which caused your results to be different.

Content: too much animation and filter. complete waste of time. duration could be cut short without them
Reply content: Can you please share which features specifically you found difficult to use? Please contact us at support@arcticshores.com.

Content: This didn't make any sense to me, im applying for the Fire servise and feel this had nothing to do with it at all, if this is what they use to deside who is going to be good for the job, its a major problem on the recruitment front.

I understand the idea and perhaps the theories of psychometric science that are quoted when justifying the existence of the app and I can fully get behind testing the idea. What I cannot get behind is using this as a tool to screen potential candidates. Solving multi armed bandit problems, impossible infinite tasks and classical prisoner dilemmas may give you insights on some of the evaluated individuals characteristics, but by no means are they a measure of what led to these specific decisions. The results of the test appear to be mostly conjecture and guesses, in many ways easy to influence by biases, algorithmic or otherwise. If this becomes the norm I would very much encourage people to learn about the classical problems I mentioned, we practice for interviews, test and exams, why should you not practice before these?
Reply content: Hello Mateusz, I wanted to clarify why we do not suggest practice for this assessment. The assessment is meant to measure intuitive behaviour, which is best gathered by focusing on the first completion. We rigorously test and retest these models, but as a psychometrics, there is noise in our measurement. To talk contact support@arcticshores.com

Content:
This test is a bit too long for my taste. It tries to make you entertain 
but it is a bit confusing. The second game is a pure luck system with no 
real rules. It is I guess how you react on carrot and stick purposes. The 
same applies to the powercut thing. I did not find those tests interesting 
nor intellectually entertaining. I just wanted to basically finish the test 
as fast As I could. Other puzzles with arrows, patterns to replicate and 
3letrician/mechanics were fun as they are real games. The facial expression 
game was quite misleading. Real people will help as graphics are ambigous. 
It is however an interesting concept yet, even if it is mapped to employer 
values. I find the result inaccurate and irrelevant. Gaming behavior and 
human interaction/personality/ work ethics are different and I will find 
unfair for an employer to base appraisal/career progression based on this.
Chato Demais!

Otherwise, a good testing measure, nice idea

Content: I would prefer to take this assessment on my laptop. Why is this not a web application? Then everyone can choose whether a phone is really the best device... The mobile screen is just way too small and in general manipulation with my phone distracted me from thinking about the tasks. Also an option for skipping the task would be useful.

If score doesn't matter and just for fun the app should specify at start. Face game some of the expressions are near identical, and many can be wrongly allocated neutral before you see other images of the same character

DO NOT COMPLETE THIS ASSESMENT ON YOUR PC!!! There's option to use on windows but my colleague used a computer and it puts you at a huge disadvantage! I did the mobile version and because of the amount of clicking and the actual type of activities you have to complete, I reccomend if you really want an accurate result to use a mobile or tablet as it's almost impossible to do the speed clicking with a mouse. If you want a fighting chance use your mobile and you will understand why on test day!

Content: Perhaps a useful suite of tests for some high-pressure workplaces, but like other reviewers, I feel that the emphasis on reaction time and visual processing obscures the measurement of behavioural traits such as persistence. I would recommend that employers not overemphasise this tool in their assessment process.
Reply content: Hi Jessica. Thank you for your feedback. Please be assured psychometric science forms the foundation of our assessments. We have also been very careful to avoid the issues associated with WEIRD samples. Indeed, the assessment has been used by and validated against all different kinds of demographics. Nonetheless, we appreciate your feedback!

Content: Overall, it was an enjoyable experience. This assessment is solely game- based and explores between others your attention to detail and memory skills, and your ability to use your logic. I'd say I was a pretty self aware person and don't agree with most of the report. That may well be me being deluded but I think it shows limitations of this kind of testing. Maybe it would be more effective if not so long?!
Reply content: Hi Rachel. Thanks for your feedback. The assessment measures behavioural and cognitive traits, and the report illustrates these in relation to a control group of similar individuals (for example, UK graduates). In terms of the length, we are currently working on making our assessments shorter.

Content: Bit of a drag

It is quite alright but not a perfect behavioural test. For example, task one is very logically designed to check the ability how one can remember things. Although I wasn't content with the safe lock task at all. It went so frustrating after about 30 mins with only 16 keys, and I gave up. I honestly thought this had no real connection with real-world problems except how fast you react to something and how keen you are. A human attention span is merely 8 seconds and that was a difficult task

It was frustrating at first coz my phone didn't support but when i did It on a friends phone i found that the concept of it was amazing. I enjoyed it. Some of them can be frustrating at times lol and some of them needs to be explained abit more. Some games need to replaced. But i loved it. I would recommend this anytime that those 5 hrs assessment anytime lol

I was quite surprised that I did pretty badly at the facial expression round, I've done the same excersize at university with real human photos subtly changed to show micro expressions as used by Paul ekman, and I was the only person in class to correctly identify all the expressions; found it more difficult to do the same thing for the animated faces admittedly. Interesting app, just not sure that the results correlate to accurate findings. I am BPS accredited in psychometric test administration and scoring, so this was quite a different experience.

Overall I'm satisfied with the experience but there are several issues. 1) you should change the faces challenge. Or maybe see the data and change the faces that most people do wrong. 2) Score means nothing without a total to compare it to. Also some info about the score would be useful. Is the score sth like an iq result? Is it average? Is it below or above average... Some stats anyway
Reply content: Thank you for your review. We are glad that you enjoyed the experience and will pass on your feedback about the emotional recognition level. The score that you see at the end is there purely for enjoyment and has no bearing on your psychometric results.

Content: I enjoyed the game although I think it required fast eye - hand coordination. I also think that specifically the cognitive abilities are measured by that. I have read the response to the same prompt saying it's all based in psychometric. Still, without knowing exactly what task measured what skill and how I remained not totally convinced by its reliability. I have started to do some research on this subject, if anyone wants to talk about his/her experience please get in touch.

Enjoyable, imaginative and well thought out games except 2 requiring fast hand/eye co-ordination. I enjoyed all of the games for what they tested and the parts of my brain that they exercised. The only draw back was that one game sped up so quickly in its early stage that I do not believe it registered my correct answer and 2 games tested the same fast hand/co-ordination which was frustrating for me as a person with Dyspraxia.

Content: I highly recommend this app for psychometric tests, it test your strength when it comes to problem solving and being able to memorize things, one could see where he/she lacking and where his/her strong points are.
Absolutely loved it. Very fun and challenging, it gets fustrating at some points but just shake it off and keep at it, never give up. If you want a challenge, this be the one.

Good application it certainly challenges different skills and tendencies, maybe as much as really bad chess, which despite not being as difficult in some ways as the Princes app at grand master level would have the average player swearing by the end of the first ten levels. B-)

As an app, this is effectively made and pretty well optimised for new phones. As a psychometric test, it fails to understand and aptly reflect the importance of certain abilities - this will be a serious demotivator for some applicants.
Reply content: Hi Mark, thank you for your feedback. Please be assured psychometric science forms the foundation of our assessments. The tasks are measuring aspects of cognition & personality that are important for the role.
